
Relationships
Artist ↔ Album – One-to-Many

Album.artist_id → Artist.artist_id (FK, NOT NULL)
Album ↔ Genre – Many-to-Many (via join table)

Album_Genre.album_id → Album.album_id (FK)
Album_Genre.genre_id → Genre.genre_id (FK)
Both foreign keys in Album_Genre together form the primary key, 
enforcing uniqueness of each album-genre pairing.

---

Flyway is currently DISABLED in your main application.

However, in your test configuration (application-test.yml, lines 20-22):

flyway:  enabled: true  locations: classpath:db/migration
flyway:
  enabled: true
  locations: classpath:db/migration
Flyway IS enabled for tests and looks for migration scripts in db/migration/.

How Flyway Works:
Create the migration directory (if it doesn't exist):

src/main/resources/db/migration/
Add migration files with specific naming:

V1__Initial_Schema.sql (version 1)
V2__Add_Genre_Table.sql (version 2)
V3__Add_Indexes.sql (version 3)
Pattern: V{version}__{description}.sql
When your app starts (if Flyway is enabled):

Flyway checks which migrations have run (tracks in flyway_schema_history table)
Runs any new migrations in order
Never re-runs old migrations
To enable Flyway in production, change application.yaml:

flyway:  enabled: true  # Change from false to     true
flyway:
  enabled: true  # Change from false to true
Important Note:
Your current setup uses Hibernate's ddl-auto: update (line 20 in application.yaml), which automatically creates/updates tables based on your JPA entities. This conflicts with Flyway. You should choose ONE approach:

Option A: Use Flyway (recommended for production)
Set flyway.enabled: true
Set jpa.hibernate.ddl-auto: validate (or none)
Option B: Use Hibernate auto-update (easier for development)
Keep flyway.enabled: false
Keep jpa.hibernate.ddl-auto: update

