2️⃣ Running docker compose up -d
Install Docker first.

Windows: download Docker Desktop (https://www.docker.com/products/docker-desktop).
macOS: Docker Desktop for Mac.
Linux: install the docker and docker-compose packages from your distro (e.g. apt install docker.io docker-compose on Ubuntu).
After installation, make sure the daemon is running (docker info should print a bunch of details).

Open a terminal (PowerShell, CMD, Git‑Bash, or any shell) in the project root – the folder that contains Dockerfile and docker-compose.yml.

Build & start the stack

# This will pull the MySQL image (if not cached), build your app image,
# then start both containers in detached mode.
docker compose up -d
Docker Compose will read the docker-compose.yml, create a network called (by default) music-library_default, start a MySQL container, then start your Spring Boot container and connect it to the same network.

Verify

docker compose ps          # shows the two containers running
docker logs music-library_app-1   # tail the Spring Boot logs
The Spring Boot log should say something like Started MusicLibraryApplication and you’ll see the MySQL connection URL printed (jdbc:mysql://mysql:3306/music_library).

Stop / clean up

docker compose down        # stops containers and removes the network
docker compose down -v     # also removes the anonymous volume that holds the DB data
3️⃣ What “containerisation” actually means
Concept	Plain‑English description
Container	A lightweight, isolated runtime environment that bundles your application code + its runtime dependencies (JDK, libraries, native binaries) together with a filesystem snapshot (the image). It shares the host OS kernel but otherwise behaves like a tiny virtual machine.
Image	A read‑only template that Docker uses to spin up containers. An image is built from a Dockerfile.
Dockerfile	A script that tells Docker how to assemble the image (base OS, copy source, run mvn package, set the entry‑point, expose ports, etc.).
Docker Engine	The daemon that actually builds images, runs containers, manages networks and storage.
Docker Compose	A YAML file that describes multiple containers (services) and how they should be wired together (networks, volumes, environment variables). It’s perfect for a multi‑service stack like app + MySQL.
Portability	Because the image contains everything except the kernel, you can copy the image (or push it to a registry) and run it on any machine that has Docker – Windows, macOS, Linux, cloud VMs, CI runners, etc. No “install Java, install MySQL” steps on the target host.
Think of a container as a self‑contained zip file that can be executed. When you run docker run … Docker creates a sandbox, mounts the image’s filesystem, allocates its own PID/NET/IPC namespaces, and starts the process you defined (java -jar app.jar). The process thinks it’s running on a clean Linux system, even though it’s sharing the host kernel.

4️⃣ Free (or low‑cost) places to host a Dockerised Spring Boot + MySQL app
Platform	Free tier details	How you push your image
Render (render.com)	750 hrs/month of a free web service (≈ 1 vCPU, 512 MiB RAM). Free PostgreSQL/MySQL add‑on (256 MiB).	Connect a GitHub repo → Render builds the Dockerfile automatically. No manual docker push needed.
Fly.io	3 small‑instance credits per month (enough for a tiny app). Free managed Postgres (up to 20 GB).	flyctl launch creates a Fly app, you push with flyctl deploy.
Railway	$5 worth of credits each month (≈ 500 hrs). Free PostgreSQL/MySQL add‑on.	Connect repo → Railway builds Dockerfile, or use railway up locally.
Google Cloud Run	2 million request‑seconds per month (≈ 1 vCPU·hour) + 1 GiB outbound traffic. Cloud SQL (MySQL) can be used in the free tier.	Build image locally, push to Artifact Registry (gcloud builds submit --tag REGION-docker.pkg.dev/PROJECT_ID/cloudrun/app), then gcloud run deploy.
Microsoft Azure Container Apps	1 GiB memory + 1 vCPU for free (per region) + free Azure Database for MySQL (basic tier).	Push image to Azure Container Registry, then create a Container App from the portal or CLI.
Amazon ECS/Fargate (Free Tier)	750 hours of Fargate per month for the first 12 months, plus 30 GB of EFS storage. Free tier RDS MySQL (750 hrs).	Build image, push to Amazon ECR, then create an ECS service.
Heroku (Docker)	Free dyno (550‑1000 hrs/month) – you must sleep after 30 min of inactivity. Add‑on ClearDB MySQL has a free tier (limited).	heroku container:login, heroku create, heroku container:push web, heroku container:release web.
GitHub Packages / GitHub Container Registry (as a registry) + GitHub Actions to deploy to any of the above clouds.	Free storage for public images, limited private storage.	docker push ghcr.io/<owner>/<repo>:tag.
Key take‑away: Heroku is not the only free option. Render, Fly.io, Railway, and the major cloud providers all give you a modest amount of free compute that is more than enough for a boot‑camp demo or a personal portfolio project.

5️⃣ Putting it all together – a quick “one‑click” workflow
Write the Dockerfile (already provided in the earlier answer).

Add docker-compose.yml (also provided).

Commit both files to your GitHub repo.

git add Dockerfile docker-compose.yml
git commit -m "Add Docker support"
git push origin main
Choose a free host (e.g. Render).

On Render, click New → Web Service, connect your GitHub repo, and select “Docker” as the environment.
Render will automatically run docker build using the Dockerfile, then start the container.
In the “Environment” tab, add the same environment variables you have in application.yaml (SPRING_DATASOURCE_URL, SPRING_DATASOURCE_USERNAME, SPRING_DATASOURCE_PASSWORD). Render also offers a managed MySQL add‑on – just bind it and use the provided URL.
Deploy – Render (or Fly.io, Railway, etc.) will build the image, push it to its internal registry, and start the container. You’ll get a public HTTPS URL (e.g. https://music-library.onrender.com) that points directly to your Spring Boot API.

Test – open Swagger UI at https://<your‑host>/swagger-ui.html or call the endpoints with Postman.

Iterate – every push to main (or whichever branch you configure) triggers a new build/deploy automatically.




