Section 5 – Migrations, Docker, & Deployment
Below is a step‑by‑step roadmap that you can copy‑paste into your project. It will give you:

Version‑controlled database schema with Flyway.
Dockerfile to containerise the Spring Boot app.
docker‑compose.yml to spin up both MySQL and the app together (so reviewers can run a single command).
Production‑ready configuration (disable ddl-auto=update, use Flyway for schema changes).
Optional CI snippet (GitHub Actions) that builds the Docker image and runs the tests.
5.1 Add Flyway to the project
5.1.1 Dependency
Add Flyway (the community edition is free and sufficient for this demo) to pom.xml inside <dependencies>:

<!-- Flyway – database migration tool -->
<dependency>
    <groupId>org.flywaydb</groupId>
    <artifactId>flyway-core</artifactId>
</dependency>
5.1.2 Disable auto‑DDL (you already have ddl-auto: none)
Your application.yml already contains:

spring:
  jpa:
    hibernate:
      ddl-auto: none   # <-- keep this
That tells Hibernate not to create/alter tables at startup. Flyway will be the sole source of truth for the schema.

5.1.3 Create the first migration script
Flyway looks for files named V<version>__<description>.sql under src/main/resources/db/migration.
Create the folder (if it doesn’t exist) and add V1__initial_schema.sql.

Path: src/main/resources/db/migration/V1__initial_schema.sql

-- -------------------------------------------------
-- 1️⃣  Initial schema for the Music Library app
-- -------------------------------------------------

-- 1️⃣ Artists
CREATE TABLE artist (
    artist_id   BIGINT NOT NULL AUTO_INCREMENT,
    name        VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL,
    description TEXT,
    created_at  TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,
    updated_at  TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP ON UPDATE CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,
    PRIMARY KEY (artist_id)
) ENGINE=InnoDB DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8mb4;

-- 2️⃣ Genres
CREATE TABLE genre (
    genre_id    BIGINT NOT NULL AUTO_INCREMENT,
    name        VARCHAR(100) NOT NULL,
    description TEXT,
    created_at  TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,
    updated_at  TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP ON UPDATE CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,
    PRIMARY KEY (genre_id)
) ENGINE=InnoDB DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8mb4;

-- 3️⃣ Albums
CREATE TABLE album (
    album_id        BIGINT NOT NULL AUTO_INCREMENT,
    title           VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL,
    release_date    DATE,
    catalog_number  VARCHAR(50) UNIQUE,
    track_count     INT,
    cover_image_url VARCHAR(255),
    artist_id       BIGINT NOT NULL,
    created_at      TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,
    updated_at      TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP ON UPDATE CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,
    PRIMARY KEY (album_id),
    CONSTRAINT fk_album_artist FOREIGN KEY (artist_id)
        REFERENCES artist (artist_id)
        ON DELETE RESTRICT
        ON UPDATE CASCADE
) ENGINE=InnoDB DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8mb4;

-- 4️⃣ Join table album_genre (many‑to‑many)
CREATE TABLE album_genre (
    album_id BIGINT NOT NULL,
    genre_id BIGINT NOT NULL,
    created_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,
    updated_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP ON UPDATE CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,
    PRIMARY KEY (album_id, genre_id),
    CONSTRAINT fk_ag_album FOREIGN KEY (album_id)
        REFERENCES album (album_id)
        ON DELETE CASCADE
        ON UPDATE CASCADE,
    CONSTRAINT fk_ag_genre FOREIGN KEY (genre_id)
        REFERENCES genre (genre_id)
        ON DELETE CASCADE
        ON UPDATE CASCADE
) ENGINE=InnoDB DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8mb4;
Why this matters

Version control – Every future schema change will be a new V2__…, V3__… file.
Idempotent – Flyway tracks which scripts have already been applied in the flyway_schema_history table, so you can safely redeploy.
Database‑agnostic – The same scripts work for MySQL, MariaDB, or even H2 (for tests) if you keep the syntax portable.
5.1.4 Verify Flyway runs locally
Run the app once (or just ./mvnw spring-boot:run). You should see Flyway output in the console:

2025-11-16 10:55:12.345  INFO 12345 --- [           main] o.f.c.i.DatabaseInitializer          : Successfully validated 1 migration (execution time 00:00.012s)
2025-11-16 10:55:12.350  INFO 12345 --- [           main] o.f.c.i.DatabaseInitializer          : Creating schema history table "flyway_schema_history"
2025-11-16 10:55:12.360  INFO 12345 --- [           main] o.f.c.i.DatabaseInitializer          : Migrating schema to version 1 - Initial schema
If you get errors about missing tables, double‑check that your MySQL instance is running and the credentials in application.yml match.

5.2 Dockerising the application
5.2.1 Dockerfile (multi‑stage build)
Create a file Dockerfile in the project root (same level as pom.xml).

# ---------- Stage 1: Build ----------
FROM eclipse-temurin:17-jdk-alpine AS builder

# Maven wrapper + source code
WORKDIR /app
COPY .mvn .mvn
COPY mvnw pom.xml ./
RUN ./mvnw dependency:go-offline -B   # pre‑download deps (speed up later builds)

# Copy source and build the jar
COPY src src
RUN ./mvnw -DskipTests package -B

# ---------- Stage 2: Runtime ----------
FROM eclipse-temurin:17-jre-alpine

# Create a non‑root user (good practice)
ARG USER=appuser
ARG UID=1000
RUN addgroup -S ${USER} && adduser -S -G ${USER} -u ${UID} ${USER}

# Copy the jar from the builder stage
COPY --from=builder /app/target/music-library-0.0.1-SNAPSHOT.jar /app/music-library.jar

# Expose the default Spring Boot port
EXPOSE 8080

# Run as non‑root
USER ${USER}

# Entry point
ENTRYPOINT ["java","-jar","/app/music-library.jar"]
Explanation

Stage 1 compiles the project with Maven (skipping tests – they’ll be run in CI).
Stage 2 uses a lightweight JRE Alpine image, copies the built JAR, and runs it as a non‑root user.
The resulting image is only ~70 MB.
5.2.2 docker‑compose.yml (MySQL + app)
Create docker-compose.yml in the same folder.

version: "3.9"

services:
  db:
    image: mysql:8.0
    container_name: music-library-db
    environment:
      MYSQL_DATABASE: music_library
      MYSQL_USER: music_library
      MYSQL_PASSWORD: music_library
      MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD: root_password   # you can change it
    ports:
      - "3306:3306"
    volumes:
      - db_data:/var/lib/mysql
    healthcheck:
      test: ["CMD", "mysqladmin", "ping", "-h", "localhost"]
      interval: 5s
      timeout: 2s
      retries: 5

  app:
    build: .
    container_name: music-library-app
    depends_on:
      db:
        condition: service_healthy
    environment:
      SPRING_DATASOURCE_URL: jdbc:mysql://db:3306/music_library?useSSL=false&allowPublicKeyRetrieval=true
      SPRING_DATASOURCE_USERNAME: music_library
      SPRING_DATASOURCE_PASSWORD: music_library
      # Optional: turn on debug logging for the container
      # LOGGING_LEVEL_ROOT: DEBUG
    ports:
      - "8080:8080"
    restart: unless-stopped

volumes:
  db_data:
Key points

The MySQL container is named db; the Spring Boot app connects to it via the hostname db.
The SPRING_DATASOURCE_URL overrides the values you have in application.yml – this is the typical “12‑factor” approach (environment variables win over file config).
depends_on with condition: service_healthy ensures the app only starts after MySQL reports it’s ready.
5.2.3 Build & run locally
rem From the project root:
docker compose build          # builds the app image + pulls MySQL
docker compose up -d          # starts both containers in detached mode
Wait a few seconds, then check:

docker compose logs -f app   # tail the app logs
You should see Flyway migrating the schema and the Spring Boot startup banner.
Open a browser (or Postman) to http://localhost:8080/swagger-ui.html – the Swagger UI should be reachable, proving the whole stack works inside Docker.

Stop & clean up

docker compose down -v   # stops containers and removes the volume (drops DB)
5.3 Production‑ready configuration tweaks
Setting	Why it matters	How to set it
Disable dev‑only logging	Reduce noise in production logs.	In src/main/resources/application.yml add: logging.level.root=INFO (or WARN).
Enable Flyway baseline (if you ever adopt an existing DB)	Prevents Flyway from trying to re‑apply old scripts.	spring.flyway.baseline-on-migrate=true (optional).
Externalize secrets	Never hard‑code passwords in the repo.	Use environment variables (SPRING_DATASOURCE_PASSWORD) – already done in docker‑compose.yml.
Health endpoint	Kubernetes / Docker health checks.	Spring Boot Actuator (spring-boot-starter-actuator) – add the dependency if you want /actuator/health.
Graceful shutdown	Allows in‑flight requests to finish.	Spring Boot already handles SIGTERM; you can set server.shutdown=graceful in application.yml.
Add the Actuator dependency (optional but nice for demos):

<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-actuator</artifactId>
</dependency>
Then expose it in application.yml:

management:
  endpoints:
    web:
      exposure:
        include: health,info
Now http://localhost:8080/actuator/health will return {"status":"UP"}.

5.4 CI/CD – GitHub Actions (optional but impressive)
Create .github/workflows/ci.yml (you can add this later; it won’t affect local development).

name: CI – Build, Test, Docker

on:
  push:
    branches: [ main, develop ]
  pull_request:
    branches: [ main ]

jobs:
  build-test:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - name: Checkout code
        uses: actions/checkout@v4

      - name: Set up JDK 17
        uses: actions/setup-java@v4
        with:
          distribution: temurin
          java-version: 17
          cache: maven

      - name: Build & run tests
        run: ./mvnw -B verify   # runs tests, generates JaCoCo report

      - name: Upload JaCoCo report
        uses: actions/upload-artifact@v4
        with:
          name: jacoco-report
          path: target/site/jacoco

  docker:
    needs: build-test
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - name: Checkout code
        uses: actions/checkout@v4

      - name: Set up Docker Buildx
        uses: docker/setup-buildx-action@v3

      - name: Login to Docker Hub (optional – if you push images)
        uses: docker/login-action@v3
        with:
          username: ${{ secrets.DOCKER_HUB_USER }}
          password: ${{ secrets.DOCKER_HUB_TOKEN }}

      - name: Build Docker image
        run: |
          docker build -t ${{ github.repository }}:${{ github.sha }} .
          docker tag ${{ github.repository }}:${{ github.sha }} ${{ github.repository }}:latest

      - name: Push image (optional)
        if: github.ref == 'refs/heads/main'
        run: |
          docker push ${{ github.repository }}:${{ github.sha }}
          docker push ${{ github.repository }}:latest
What this does

Builds the project and runs all tests (verify includes test + integration-test).
Generates a JaCoCo coverage report and uploads it as an artifact (you can download it from the GitHub UI).
Builds the Docker image using the same Dockerfile.
(Optional) Pushes the image to Docker Hub when you merge to main.
You can skip the Docker‑push steps if you don’t have a Docker Hub account – just keep the build part.

