High‑level verdict
Your current model (Artist ↔ Album ↔ Genre) is a perfectly reasonable core for a music‑library demo. It demonstrates:

JPA entity relationships (one‑to‑many, many‑to‑many)
Spring‑Boot REST controllers with full CRUD
Use of Lombok, Bean Validation, and an embedded MySQL/Tomcat stack
That alone will look solid to most hiring managers who care about backend fundamentals.

However, a final‑project that stands out should also show that you thought about real‑world concerns (data quality, API ergonomics, testing, documentation, security, and extensibility). Below are concrete, prioritized recommendations you can implement before you start bulk‑loading data.

1️⃣ Domain model refinements
Change	Why it matters	Quick implementation
Add a catalogNumber (or externalId) column to Album	Many physical releases are identified by a label catalog number (e.g., SILKA022B). It lets a user search for a specific pressing and shows you can store “business‑key” data that isn’t the primary key.	java @Column(name="catalog_number", length=50, unique=true) private String catalogNumber;  Add the field to the DTO/JSON payload and to the AlbumService.create/update methods.
Add trackCount (or a separate Track entity)	Gives the library a bit more depth. Even a simple integer shows you can extend the model without breaking existing APIs.	Add private Integer trackCount; to Album. If you want a full Track entity later, you already have the many‑to‑many groundwork (Album ↔ Genre).
Add releaseDate (full LocalDate) instead of just releaseYear	Some compilations span multiple years; a precise date is more useful for sorting/filtering. Keep releaseYear as a derived read‑only field if you still need it.	java private LocalDate releaseDate; @Transient public Integer getReleaseYear() { return releaseDate != null ? releaseDate.getYear() : null; }
Add coverImageUrl (String)	Modern music apps display album art. Even a placeholder URL shows you considered UI consumption.	Simple String coverImageUrl; column.
Normalize description to notes	Consistency across entities (Artist.notes, Album.notes, Genre.notes).	Rename fields or add alias getters.
Make the many‑to‑many side bidirectional (Genre ↔ Album) – already done with mappedBy = "genres" – just expose a addAlbum/removeAlbum helper in GenreService for symmetry.	Shows you can manage relationships from either side.	Add analogous methods in GenreService.

2️⃣ API ergonomics
Recommendation	Benefit	How to add
DTOs (Data Transfer Objects) instead of exposing JPA entities directly	Prevents accidental lazy‑loading leaks, decouples persistence from the contract, and makes versioning easier.	Create AlbumDto, ArtistDto, GenreDto. Use MapStruct or manual mapping in the service layer.
Pagination & sorting (Pageable) on list endpoints (GET /api/albums?page=0&size=20&sort=releaseDate,desc)	Real‑world APIs rarely return entire tables; it shows you understand scalability.	Change List<Album> to Page<AlbumDto> and accept Pageable as a method argument.
Search / filter endpoint (GET /api/albums/search?title=promised&year=1997)	Demonstrates query‑by‑example or Specification pattern.	Add a AlbumSpecification class and a search method in AlbumRepository.
Standardised error responses (e.g., { "timestamp": "...", "status": 404, "error": "Not Found", "message": "Album 42 not found", "path": "/api/albums/42" })	Improves client experience and shows you can handle exceptions globally.	Create a @ControllerAdvice with @ExceptionHandler(ResourceNotFoundException.class).
OpenAPI / Swagger UI (springdoc-openapi-ui)	Instantly gives recruiters a browsable API doc.	Add dependency org.springdoc:springdoc-openapi-starter-webmvc-ui and annotate controllers with @Operation, @Parameter.
HATEOAS links (optional)	Shows awareness of REST hypermedia principles.	Return EntityModel<AlbumDto> with linkTo(methodOn(...)).

3️⃣ Validation & data integrity
What to validate	How
Non‑blank name/title	@NotBlank on fields.
Catalog number uniqueness	@Column(unique = true) + handle DataIntegrityViolationException in the global handler.
Release year range (1900‑2100)	@Min(1900) @Max(2100) on releaseYear.
Genre name uniqueness	Same as catalog number.
DTO‑level validation	Annotate DTO fields and add @Valid on controller method parameters.

4️⃣ Testing – make it show‑ready
Test type	Why it impresses	Quick starter
Unit tests for services (mock repositories with Mockito)	Shows you can isolate business logic.	@ExtendWith(MockitoExtension.class) + @InjectMocks.
Integration tests with @SpringBootTest + TestRestTemplate (or MockMvc)	Verifies the whole stack, including JPA mappings.	Write one test per CRUD operation; use an in‑memory H2 DB (@ActiveProfiles("test")).
Contract tests (e.g., using Spring Cloud Contract) – optional	Demonstrates API‑first mindset.	Generate stubs from OpenAPI spec.
Coverage report (jacoco)	Employers love a coverage badge.	Add jacoco-maven-plugin and enforce >80% line coverage.

5️⃣ Persistence & deployment considerations
Idea	Reason	Implementation tip
Flyway or Liquibase migrations	Keeps DB schema versioned, easier to demo on a fresh machine.	Add flyway-core dependency and place V1__init.sql in src/main/resources/db/migration.
Dockerfile + docker‑compose (MySQL + app)	One‑click reproducible environment – great for interviews.	Multi‑stage Dockerfile (builder → runtime) and a docker-compose.yml that spins up MySQL with the same credentials you use locally.
Profile‑specific configuration (application-dev.yml, application-prod.yml)	Shows you understand environment separation.	Move DB credentials to application-dev.yml; keep defaults in application.yml.
Health endpoint (/actuator/health)	Gives a quick sanity check; part of production‑grade monitoring.	Add spring-boot-starter-actuator and expose health in management.endpoints.web.exposure.include.

6️⃣ Security (lightweight but impressive)
Feature	Benefit
Basic auth (username/password from application.yml)	Protects the API from casual browsing; easy to demo with Postman.
Spring Security JWT (optional)	Shows modern token‑based auth; can be a separate branch if you don’t want to over‑engineer.
Method‑level security (@PreAuthorize("hasRole('ADMIN')") on delete endpoints)	Demonstrates role‑based access control.
Implementation tip: start with spring-boot-starter-security and configure an in‑memory user (admin/admin). All other endpoints stay open, but the DELETE calls require authentication.

7️⃣ Documentation & presentation
README.md – include:

Project overview (what problem it solves).
Architecture diagram (entities ↔ relationships).
Build/run instructions (Maven, Docker).
Example curl/ARC commands (the JSON you asked for).
Test coverage badge (e.g., from Codecov or shields.io).
Architecture diagram (draw.io or Mermaid) – quickly visualise the three entities and the join table.

Live demo – if possible, push the Docker image to Docker Hub and give a short video or a hosted instance (Heroku, Render, Railway). Even a local Docker‑Compose screenshot in the README looks professional.

8️⃣ Prioritised “next‑step” checklist
Priority	Action
High	Add catalogNumber (or externalId) to Album.
High	Switch to DTOs + MapStruct (or manual mapper).
Medium	Implement pagination (Pageable) on list endpoints.
Medium	Add global exception handler + standard error payload.
Medium	Add OpenAPI/Swagger UI (springdoc-openapi-ui).
Low	Add Track entity (optional) or at least trackCount.
Low	Dockerize the app + compose with MySQL.
Low	Write a handful of unit + integration tests (coverage >80%).
Low	Add basic auth or JWT for delete operations.
You can tackle the high‑priority items in a single day; the medium‑priority ones will take another day or two; the low‑priority enhancements can be added incrementally as time permits.

Bottom line
Your foundation is solid. By adding a few domain fields, cleaning up the API surface with DTOs, pagination, and proper error handling, and showcasing testing, documentation, and deployment, you’ll turn a functional school project into a portfolio‑ready showcase that signals to employers you understand the full lifecycle of a Spring‑Boot microservice.




